  "opinion": "As a 43-year-old immigrant man living in Chicago, unemployed with a primary school education, I spend several hours daily on social media, and dealing with fake content is a real concern for me. My background as an immigrant makes me cautious about misinformation that could affect my family or community, especially since I have a child and am in a relationship. I rely on social media to stay connected with loved ones back home and for news, but I've learned to be very careful. My personality traits, like high conscientiousness and agreeableness, mean I take this seriously and want to help others avoid harm, while my high neuroticism makes me anxious about the spread of lies. To manage fake content, I start by checking sources before sharing anything. If a post seems too sensational or doesn't come from a trusted news outlet, I ignore it. I also use fact-checking websites when I'm unsure, which helps me feel more secure. Since I'm not very open to new ideas, I stick to familiar platforms and groups where people I trust share information. My hobbies, like cooking and knitting, keep me grounded, and I apply that same patience to social media by taking my time to verify things. I believe it's important to talk to my family about this, teaching my child to question what they see online. As a Hindu, I value truth and honesty, which guides me to avoid spreading fake content. Overall, I think the best way to deal with fake content is to be responsible, use common sense, and encourage others to do the same, creating a safer online space for everyone.",
